"Spindler N., Galvosas P., Pohlmeier A., Vereecken H.","NMR velocimetry with 13-interval stimulated echo multi-slice imaging in natural porous media under low flow rates",2011,"Journal of Magnetic Resonance","212","1",,"216","223",,,10.1016/j.jmr.2011.07.004,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-84855376534&partnerID=40&md5=91ccc9d682608f72c84e281b52b5d218","Forschungszentrum Juelich, Institute of Bio-and Geosciences - Agrosphere, 52425 Juelich, Germany; MacDiarmid Institute for Advanced Materials and Nanotechnology, School of Chemical and Physical Sciences, Victoria University of Wellington, Wellington 6001, New Zealand","Spindler, N., Forschungszentrum Juelich, Institute of Bio-and Geosciences - Agrosphere, 52425 Juelich, Germany; Galvosas, P., MacDiarmid Institute for Advanced Materials and Nanotechnology, School of Chemical and Physical Sciences, Victoria University of Wellington, Wellington 6001, New Zealand; Pohlmeier, A., Forschungszentrum Juelich, Institute of Bio-and Geosciences - Agrosphere, 52425 Juelich, Germany; Vereecken, H., Forschungszentrum Juelich, Institute of Bio-and Geosciences - Agrosphere, 52425 Juelich, Germany","Characterization and quantification of root water uptake processes play a key role in understanding and managing the effects of global climate change on agricultural production and ecosystem dynamics. Part of this understanding is related to the flow of water towards plant roots in soils. In this study we demonstrate for the first time, to our knowledge, that fluid flow in the voids of the pore space of a model soil system (natural sand) can be detected and mapped to an NMR image for mean flows as low as 0.06 mm/s even under the influence of internal magnetic field gradients. To accomplish this we combined multi-slice imaging with a 13-interval pulse sequence to the NMR pulse sequence 13-interval stimulated echo multislice imaging (13-interval STEMSI). The result is a largely reduced influence of the internal magnetic field gradients, leading to an improved signal-to-noise ratio which in turn enables one to acquire velocity maps where conventional stimulated echo methods fail. © 2011 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.","Internal magnetic field gradients; Natural porous media; NMR flow mapping","silicon dioxide; water; algorithm; article; artifact; calibration; computer simulation; electromagnetic field; image processing; metabolism; methodology; normal distribution; nuclear magnetic resonance imaging; plant root; porosity; signal noise ratio; soil; Algorithms; Artifacts; Calibration; Computer Simulation; Electromagnetic Fields; Image Processing, Computer-Assisted; Magnetic Resonance Imaging; Normal Distribution; Plant Roots; Porosity; Signal-To-Noise Ratio; Silicon Dioxide; Soil; Water; Agricultural productions; Echo methods; Ecosystem dynamics; Flow mapping; Global climate changes; Internal magnetic field gradients; Mean flow; Multi slices; Natural sand; NMR images; Plant roots; Pore space; Pulse sequence; Root-water uptake; Soil systems; Velocity maps; Agriculture; Climate change; Magnetic fields; Magnetic resonance imaging; Nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy; Porous materials; Geologic models",,"silicon dioxide, 10279-57-9, 14464-46-1, 14808-60-7, 15468-32-3, 60676-86-0, 7631-86-9; water, 7732-18-5; Silicon Dioxide, 7631-86-9; Soil; Water, 7732-18-5",,,,"Waisel, Y., Eshel, A., Kafkafi, U., (1991) Plant Roots: The Hidden Half, Marcel Dekker Inc., New York; Gregory, P.J., (2006) Plant Roots: Growth, Activity and Interactions with Soils, , Blackwell, Oxford; Javaux, M., Vanclooster, M., Scale-and rate-dependent solute transport within an unsaturated sandy aquifer (2003) Soil Sci. Soc. Am. J., 67, pp. 1334-1343; Weihermüller, L., Siemens, J., Deurer, M., Knoblauch, S., Rupp, H., Göttlein, A., Pütz, T., In-situ soil water extraction: A review (2007) J. Environ. Qual., 36, pp. 1735-1748; Köckenberger, W., De Panfilis, C., Santoro, D., Dahiya, P., Rawsthorne, S., High resolution 